Later it has been reported from shallow waters (0-100 m) from the Caribbean, The Mediterranean, Indian Ocean etc. It has become a pet for people studying larval stransport and there are COI sequences with that name on Genbank but cant see that any of the sequences are from the type locality. The papers that talk about it doesent include the reference to the original description in the reference list. WORMS also doesn’t have the reference….

my_notes_on_tammys: In the case of Starkus mixtus, the situation was peculiar, because at the time I identified the material, “Starkus”  was included in the polyphyletic genus Typhlotanais. As so, by calling taxon Typhlotanais aff mixtus I actually referred it to what is now a genus Starkus. Washburn_etal_2021 (some of id's odd..)

my_notes_on_tammys: Magda- Typhlotanais plebejus has a type locality in the North Atlantic. As so I am convinced that this species from the CCZ cannot be the same species. However, my PhD student has found taxa morphologically similar to T. plebejus in different parts of the world, although genetically different, so we are convinced that what we currently call T. plebejus and T. aff plebejus (like the one from the CCZ) represent a new genus. Does it make a sense for you?
